==Australia== {{see also|Nuclear power in Australia}}
*[[High Flux Australian Reactor]], a 10 MW [[DIDO class reactor]] in [[Lucas Heights, New South Wales]] that produced nuclear medicine (approximately half a million doses a year) for the diagnosis and treatment of major diseases such as cancer and heart disease. It first went critical on 26 January 1958, was shut down in January 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansto.gov.au/resources/images_of_ansto/hifar.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828141140/http://www.ansto.gov.au/resources/images_of_ansto/hifar.html|title=HIFAR|archivedate=28 August 2008|publisher=|accessdate=20 August 2015}}</ref> and is currently under a care and maintenance program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ansto.gov.au/AboutANSTO/OPAL/Decommissioningearlierreactors/ |title=Archived copy|accessdate=2014-11-05|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105133206/http://www.ansto.gov.au/AboutANSTO/OPAL/Decommissioningearlierreactors/|archivedate=5 November 2014|df=}}</ref> *[[MOATA]], 100kW [[Argonaut class reactor]], dismantled in 2009. *[[Open-pool Australian lightwater reactor]], 20 MW, a replacement for the High Flux Australian Reactor supplied by [[INVAP]] of Argentina. This facility first went critical at 11.25pm on 12 August 2006<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080720132009/http://www.ansto.gov.au/resources/images_of_ansto/opal_images2.html OPAL<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and achieved full power for the first time on 3 November 2006.
