{{SIA|rivers}}

Province flowers are [[species]] of [[plant]]s selected to represent each [[province of Sweden]]. The origin of province flowers came from the [[United States|American]] idea of [[state flowers]], and was brought to Sweden by August Wickström and Paul Petter Waldenström in 1908. Waldenström published the proposal to introduce province flowers in the May 288, 1908 edition of the newspaper ''[[Stockholms Dagblad]]'', and requested suggestions of species from the country's [[Botany|botanic]]s. A list was put together on June 7, 1908, by professor Veit B. Wittrock from the Botanical Garden in [[Stockholm]].<ref name="arbetarbladet"/> [[Scania]] and [[Hälsingland]] violently opposed the plants that were selected to represent them; Scania was given [[European Beech]] but wanted [[oxeye daisy]], while Hälsingland was given [[Scots Pine]] but wanted [[flax]]. Erik E:son Hammar, a pastor and politician in Sweden, granted the two provinces' wish to change their province flowers in 1909.<ref name="dalarna">{{cite book|last=Hamrin|first=Örjan|title=Dalarnas hembygdsbok|editor=Raihle, Jan |editor2=Ståhl, Elisabeth|publisher=Dalarnas fornminnes- och hembygdsförbund|location=[[Falun]]|date=2003|volume=73|chapter=Vilken är Dalarnas landskapsblomma?|isbn=91-87466-66-X|language=Swedish}}</ref> There is still debate amongst several other provinces over which species should represent them and they have therefore been given two province flowers.<ref name="arbetarbladet">{{cite news|url=http://arbetarbladet.se/merlasning/ulfivarshistoria/1.1028255|title=Den 100-åriga liljekonvaljen|last=Nilsson|first=Ulf|date=May 10, 2009|work=[[Arbetarbladet]]|language=Swedish|accessdate=2009-06-20|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511170921/http://arbetarbladet.se/merlasning/ulfivarshistoria/1.1028255|archivedate=May 11, 2009|df=}}</ref>
